Do IMDb Ratings Reflect Biases?

Author: Gavin South

Background

What insights can we gain from our IMDb ratings about our society?

It’s fair to say that through last decade as most people prepare to see a feature film, either at home or at the local theater, they often consult an online movie rating source to find out if the movie in question is good or not. As they scour through the various websites and blogs they generally come across, and enter, the IMDb website.

IMDb which started in the 90’s has accumulated and quantified almost every bit of information available on movies and tv shows from the past century. They are a reputable source for all information and continues to be a standard base of information for anyone to access. Interestingly what I personally use IMDb for the most, is their ratings on movies and shows. I search and read what these reviewers think about these movies and shows so that I know what to expect. I’m not alone in this.

That being said a question arises when considering these ratings and reviews… how does the largest ‘Internet Movie Data Base’ accrue the score? Well interestingly it’s the average aggregate score of all the reviews inserted by fellow cinephiles and random soccer moms alike. The score is a range from 0-10 and as you’ll see there is a vast variety of ratings. IMDb had this to say about the rating system they use. " IMDb ratings are “accurate” in the sense that they are calculated using a consistent, unbiased formula, but we don’t claim that IMDb ratings are “accurate” in an absolute qualitative sense. We offer these ratings as a simplified way to see what other IMDb users all over the world think about titles listed on our site. We believe that these ratings provide a fun and useful indication of the opinion of a movie held by the general public, but ultimately each individual is the arbiter of what is ‘good’ or ‘bad’ when it comes to judging the value of a work of art. Think of ratings more as a guide than as an incontrovertible qualitative verdict. In the final analysis, opinions about the quality of movies and TV shows are subjective, and the IMDb rating is no exception. "

Amazingly, The team at IMDb is not adding any sort of biases or agenda to their ratings, what you see is what the public feels is a an appropriate metric for the ‘art’ that they’ve watched. The scores now not only reflect the populous but also reflect the movie industry and what we are all consuming.

Ratings

Our ratings say alot about our tastes and culture

According to the IMDb website and the current entertainment industry, all films are given a rating that reflects the audience that said film is appropriate for. These ratings are; all, age 7+, 13+, 16+, and 18+. In the data base there are close to 17,000 movies ratings that date back from the early 1900’s. The ratings of these movies and the scores that we all have given these movies can actually reflect what types of movies we all think are better… R or G? Pg-13 or PG?

The question is do we as a society find one maturity level of movie better over another? Is there bias? If there is no bias, then all movie rating groups will have roughly the same average IMDb rating.

Statistical Test

There is a bias, but it’s relieving

Using an ANOVA to see if the average IMDb scores for each age group are different or alike is the best option for the vast amount of movies ratings available to us. If the results of the test are significant, then we can make some conclusions about the maturity level of the movies we like in society.

##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Age            4    491  122.83   71.28 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   7311  12598    1.72                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 38 observations deleted due to missingness

Based off the results from the ANOVA test there is a very significant difference in the average scores of age rating group. The value of the test is so low in fact that we can say without any doubt that there is bias in the data and assume the same reflects for the rest of the population.

The results bode well for our society; it appears that mature movies are rated the worse out of all other age groups, and childrens movies are rated much higher on average! What an important insight, especially considering that children don’t go to IMBd’s website to submit scores and reviews, these are reviews made by adults.

Deeper Look

Our standards are strong considering the current entertainment environment.

This test is important and it’s results are a window into our society as a whole. It’s becoming important to quantify and test data-sets like this one because our society has no doubt deteriorated from it’s humble christian beginnings. Frankly, because streaming companies like Netflix, HBO, and Amazon have made mature movies and shows exclusively for the past decade, I thought they may begin to pull our standards down. The first graph showed the ratings from all movies in the data base. This graph shows the most influential and recent years surrounding the release of streaming services.

Amazingly again, rated R movies are still rated less on average than all other Genres. I feel like someone should share these finding with the creative teams at those named companies to prompt an investment in more clean G-rated movies and shows. They would probably gain popularity!

But Disney and their streaming service Disney+ have been beacons of integrity for the movie industry and for the individuals and families that desire clean media. Look at the proportions of each rating level offered by Disney:

Disney obviously sticks with it’s family values by offering wholesome movies and shows.


Here is the same graph with Netflixs’ offerings:

And Hulus’:

And Amazon Prime Videos’:

All these streaming services have statistically different numbers of Age Ratings and associated IMDb Ratings. Running a test called a four-way ANOVA, we can see that there is a massive discrepancy between what each service provides their customers.

##                  Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## as.factor(Age)    4    491   122.8   75.28  < 2e-16 ***
## Netflix           1    407   407.2  249.54  < 2e-16 ***
## Hulu              1    142   142.0   87.04  < 2e-16 ***
## PrimeVideo        1     93    93.4   57.22 4.37e-14 ***

## Residuals      7307  11923     1.6

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 38 observations deleted due to missingness

It’s incredible to see how many mature movies are being uploaded and streamed by the largest movie subscriptions available. It’s a shame these companies think this is what sell, honestly should be reconsider and take some advice from Disney and it’s approach to media. The reviews from the whole data set support the idea that movies for everyone are better rated and accepted.

Final Thoughts

As I began looking into this data I though that people now and days would prefer mature movies and rate them higher than clean traditional films, but this is not the case. Our society, and people that submit their reviews on IMBd obviously still have high standards and rate clean movies higher than adult films. This is a relief and makes the world seem like a less corrupt place. We need more comanies like Disney to begin to reverse the status quo, to make entertainment that panders to all audiences. The repurcussions would be great and the world would do nothing but benefit from the effort. Plus, a lot of money is to be made there.
